WEBVTT

00:00:00.960 --> 00:00:05.360
Posit Cloud is an online platform where you can easily do and share data work with just a few

00:00:05.360 --> 00:00:10.720
clicks. We recently added a new feature called Data Connections which lets you securely store

00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:14.960
database credentials and share them across data projects and among your collaborators.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:20.320
In this tutorial we will demonstrate how to achieve this by using a publicly available

00:00:20.320 --> 00:00:27.120
Postgres database. Let's get started. The first thing we're going to do is create a new space.

00:00:27.120 --> 00:00:29.520
You can find this in the upper left hand nav bar.

00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:34.560
Let's go ahead and create a new space calling it RNA Project.

00:00:37.360 --> 00:00:42.959
This will create a new space for us to do work and invite others to collaborate. You can start

00:00:42.959 --> 00:00:48.080
a new project but before we do that let's go to Data. This is where you're going to add your

00:00:48.080 --> 00:00:55.439
new data connection. Click on Add Connection and we're going to make a new connection name.

00:00:56.160 --> 00:01:02.720
Let's type in RNA Central which is going to be a Postgres database. These credentials are publicly

00:01:02.720 --> 00:01:09.919
available and linked to in the description. Our user is going to be Reader. I'll paste in the

00:01:09.919 --> 00:01:18.320
password which you can find online and server. Finally we're going to go ahead and put in our

00:01:18.320 --> 00:01:26.959
port number and our database name. Once we do this we're going to click on OK.

00:01:28.879 --> 00:01:31.680
The database connection is going to be stored and saved

00:01:34.559 --> 00:01:38.800
and we're going to be able to use this in projects. Let's go back to content

00:01:39.440 --> 00:01:44.160
and now let's create a new RStudio IDE project from the drop down.

00:01:48.879 --> 00:01:54.559
While the project is loading let's rename it RNA Analysis.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:04.480
Once PositCloud is done spinning up your individualized IDE we're going to be able

00:02:04.480 --> 00:02:11.759
to access that database connection that we just defined. So if you look in the upper right hand

00:02:11.759 --> 00:02:17.679
of the IDE and move to the connections tab we're going to start a new connection

00:02:18.960 --> 00:02:22.720
and there it is the database connection we just saved RNA Central.

00:02:24.160 --> 00:02:29.039
Clicking on this is going to show you a code snippet which includes all the information

00:02:29.039 --> 00:02:38.479
including the encrypted password. Let's use a new R script to connect to and analyze the data.

00:02:39.440 --> 00:02:43.039
The first thing this is going to do is load in a necessary package

00:02:43.039 --> 00:02:48.080
and while it's doing that let's name the R script RNA Explore.

00:02:51.600 --> 00:02:54.639
From here we can then load the library that we need

00:02:55.759 --> 00:03:00.399
and the DBI library and create our first connection.

00:03:03.039 --> 00:03:06.559
The connection has been made and you can see in the connections tab

00:03:06.880 --> 00:03:10.720
all of the schemas available for this database connection.

00:03:13.440 --> 00:03:20.479
Before we make our first query let's bring in two libraries dplyr and dbplyr.

00:03:21.839 --> 00:03:26.639
Now neither of these have been installed yet but the IDE will remind me of this

00:03:26.639 --> 00:03:28.479
and we can install right away.

00:03:29.440 --> 00:03:33.759
Once these packages are ready we're going to go ahead and make a query

00:03:35.279 --> 00:03:41.839
and we can do this by using the con variable that has stored the connection that is still live.

00:03:44.559 --> 00:03:47.440
Let's go ahead and create a new variable named results.

00:03:47.679 --> 00:03:50.559
Let's go ahead and create a new variable named results.

00:03:52.479 --> 00:03:57.199
From here we're going to call the connection

00:03:58.080 --> 00:04:02.880
and then bring in the specific schema name and table that we're interested in.

00:04:06.080 --> 00:04:11.600
For now we're just going to go ahead and get the top 200 results within this table.

00:04:12.559 --> 00:04:18.959
When I run this we went to the database, we got all the information on the top 200 rows,

00:04:18.959 --> 00:04:21.600
and now we can see this in the environment.

00:04:21.600 --> 00:04:26.559
We have both our connection still and results data frame which has 200 observations.

00:04:27.359 --> 00:04:31.519
If we take a quick peek we can see the type of information that is stored

00:04:32.720 --> 00:04:38.160
and there seems to be an integer variable length for each of the observations.

00:04:38.640 --> 00:04:42.480
We can quickly turn this into a histogram to see what we're working with.

00:04:46.079 --> 00:04:54.640
Some observations are in the 0 to 500 range while many are up around 1200 or above.

00:04:56.720 --> 00:05:02.000
The best part is if you create a new project you'll be able to access the same database connection

00:05:02.239 --> 00:05:06.079
If you create a new project you'll be able to access the same database connection

00:05:07.519 --> 00:05:13.119
and if you change the information from your connection it'll automatically update in new

00:05:13.119 --> 00:05:15.519
and existing projects once it's relaunched.

00:05:16.399 --> 00:05:20.320
I hope you enjoyed learning about the new data connections feature in Posit Cloud.

00:05:21.679 --> 00:05:28.480
You can visit posit.cloud to create a free account, connect to your databases, and begin exploring.

